# Canary (honey) domains. None of these are real services.
# Goal: nothing on the LAN should ever query these. Any query is
# a configuration leak, a misclick, or a compromised host.
#
# They live in Pi-hole's local DNS so they resolve to RFC1918 nowhere
# and show up in the query log attributed to the client that asked.
#
# Naming convention: <prefix>.canary.<lab-domain>
# Pick names that look juicy — an attacker poking at /etc/hosts or
# browser history should be tempted to reach for them.
#
# Add new ones whenever you launch a new internal service or VLAN;
# put one canary per "interesting" name a real service would have.

# Internal-looking infra
admin-portal.canary.lan
backup-nas.canary.lan
ci-runner.canary.lan
dev-jumpbox.canary.lan
internal-grafana.canary.lan
secret-mgr.canary.lan

# Cloud-looking honey
aws-prod-bucket.canary.lan
gcp-secrets.canary.lan
vault-prod.canary.lan

# Looks-like-a-mistake names that get picked up by typo-squat scanners
piehole.canary.lan
admln.canary.lan
